{
  "response": "# Menu Button with Dropdown Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.  \n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA  \n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users, keyboard-only users, low vision users, users with motor impairments  \n> **Assistive technologies:** JAWS, NVDA, keyboard-only interaction  \n\n**Feature:** A reusable React menu button that opens a dropdown menu with 5-8 selectable action items, including optional disabled items and possible future nested submenus.  \n**Risk Level:** Medium  \n**Component/Page Type:** Menu Button / Dropdown Menu  \n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\nThis component provides an action menu triggered by a button labeled \u201cMenu\u201d or \u201cActions.\u201d Activating the button opens a dropdown list of selectable menu items. Users must be able to open, navigate, select, and close the menu using pointer, keyboard, and screen reader workflows.\n\nThis is not a generic disclosure or select replacement. It is an application-style action menu, so the correct accessibility model is the WAI-ARIA APG **Menu Button** pattern.\n\n**Primary APG pattern:**  \nWAI-ARIA APG Menu Button Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/menu-button/\n\n**Related APG pattern:**  \nWAI-ARIA APG Menu and Menubar Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/menubar/\n\n**Important boundary:** This plan assumes the menu contains commands or actions. If the menu is used for page navigation, a native list of links may be more appropriate. If the menu is used for selecting a value in a form, this should probably be a native `<select>`, radio group, or listbox instead.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\nThe component should use a native `<button>` as the trigger. The dropdown should be rendered as a menu container with `role=\"menu\"`, and each selectable item should use `role=\"menuitem\"` unless a specific checkbox/radio menu behavior is needed.\n\nBecause this is a reusable component, the parent page should provide the surrounding landmark and heading structure. The component itself does not create a landmark.\n\n### Structure Diagram\n\n```html\n<div class=\"menu-button-component\">\n  <button\n    type=\"button\"\n    aria-haspopup=\"menu\"\n    aria-expanded=\"false\"\n    aria-controls=\"actions-menu\"\n  >\n    Actions\n  </button>\n\n  <div\n    id=\"actions-menu\"\n    role=\"menu\"\n    aria-labelledby=\"actions-button\"\n    hidden\n  >\n    <button role=\"menuitem\">Edit</button>\n    <button role=\"menuitem\">Duplicate</button>\n    <button role=\"menuitem\" aria-disabled=\"true\">Archive</button>\n    <button role=\"menuitem\">Delete</button>\n  </div>\n</div>\n```\n\nThe exact rendered elements may be `<button role=\"menuitem\">` for command items, or `<a role=\"menuitem\">` only when the item navigates to another URL. Do not use generic clickable `<div>` elements when native interactive elements can express the behavior.\n\n**WCAG grounding:**\n\n- Native trigger button supports name, role, and value: WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n- Menu and menuitem roles communicate relationships and structure: WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships, WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n- DOM order should match visual order of menu items: WCAG 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence.\n- The button label must be visible and descriptive, such as \u201cActions\u201d or \u201cMore actions for [item name]\u201d: WCAG 2.4.6 Headings and Labels.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard Model | ARIA Attributes | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Trigger button | APG Menu Button | Enter/Space opens menu; Down Arrow opens menu and moves focus to first item; Up Arrow may open menu and move focus to last item | `aria-haspopup=\"menu\"`, `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Dropdown menu | APG Menu | Receives managed focus through its items; not itself normally tabbable | `role=\"menu\"`, `aria-labelledby` | 1.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Enabled menu item | APG Menuitem | Up/Down arrows move between items; Enter/Space activates; Escape closes menu | `role=\"menuitem\"` | 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Disabled menu item | APG Menuitem | May be focusable but not activatable, per APG menu behavior | `role=\"menuitem\"`, `aria-disabled=\"true\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Optional submenu trigger | APG Menu with submenu | Right Arrow opens submenu; Left Arrow closes submenu and returns focus to parent item | `aria-haspopup=\"menu\"`, `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n\n### Trigger Button\n\n**Pattern:** APG Menu Button  \nhttps://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/menu-button/\n\nThe trigger must be a native `<button type=\"button\">`.\n\n**Required attributes:**\n\n- `aria-haspopup=\"menu\"`: communicates that the button opens a menu. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-expanded=\"false\"` when closed and `\"true\"` when open. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-controls=\"[menu-id]\"`: references the controlled menu element. WCAG 1.3.1, 4.1.2.\n- Accessible name from visible text, such as \u201cActions.\u201d If multiple menu buttons appear in a list, include context through visible text or `aria-label`, such as \u201cActions for Quarterly Report.\u201d WCAG 2.4.6, 4.1.2.\n\n**Screen reader expectation:**\n\nWhen focused while closed, NVDA/JAWS should announce approximately:\n\n```text\nActions, menu button, collapsed\n```\n\nWhen opened:\n\n```text\nActions, menu button, expanded\n```\n\nExact phrasing varies by browser and assistive technology.\n\n### Menu Container\n\n**Pattern:** APG Menu  \nhttps://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/menubar/\n\nThe menu container should use:\n\n- `role=\"menu\"`: identifies the popup as a menu. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-labelledby=\"[button-id]\"`: associates menu with its trigger label. WCAG 1.3.1, 4.1.2.\n- `hidden`, conditional rendering, or equivalent removal from the accessibility tree when closed.\n\nWhen closed, menu items must not remain reachable by keyboard or screen reader virtual cursor as active menu content. In React, conditional rendering is preferred. If retained in DOM, use `hidden` or `display: none`; do not rely on off-screen positioning alone.\n\n### Menu Items\n\nEach action should be an interactive element with a menu role:\n\n- Use `<button role=\"menuitem\">` for commands.\n- Use `<a role=\"menuitem\" href=\"...\">` only for navigation.\n- Use `role=\"menuitemcheckbox\"` only for toggleable checked menu items.\n- Use `role=\"menuitemradio\"` only for mutually exclusive choices.\n\nDisabled items:\n\n- Use `aria-disabled=\"true\"` for disabled menu items. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Disabled items must not activate on click, Enter, or Space.\n- Disabled items may remain arrow-focusable so screen reader users can discover the unavailable option and hear that it is disabled.\n- Do not use only visual dimming to indicate disabled state. Pair visual dimming with `aria-disabled=\"true\"` and, where useful, explanatory text. WCAG 1.4.1, 4.1.2.\n\n---\n\n## Keyboard Model\n\nThe menu must follow the APG Menu Button keyboard model.\n\n### When Focus Is On The Button\n\n- **Enter:** Opens the menu and moves focus to the first enabled menu item. WCAG 2.1.1, 2.4.3.\n- **Space:** Opens the menu and moves focus to the first enabled menu item. WCAG 2.1.1, 2.4.3.\n- **Arrow Down:** Opens the menu and moves focus to the first enabled menu item. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **Arrow Up:** Opens the menu and moves focus to the last enabled menu item. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **Tab:** Moves to the next focusable element in page order without opening the menu. WCAG 2.4.3.\n\n### When Focus Is Inside The Menu\n\n- **Arrow Down:** Moves focus to the next menu item. Wrap to the first item from the last item. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **Arrow Up:** Moves focus to the previous menu item. Wrap to the last item from the first item. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **Home:** Moves focus to the first menu item. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **End:** Moves focus to the last menu item. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **Enter:** Activates the focused enabled item and closes the menu. Focus handling after activation depends on the action. WCAG 2.1.1, 2.4.3.\n- **Space:** Activates the focused enabled item and closes the menu. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **Escape:** Closes the menu and restores focus to the trigger button. WCAG 2.1.1, 2.4.3.\n- **Tab:** Closes the menu and allows focus to move to the next tabbable element in page order. This avoids creating a keyboard trap. WCAG 2.1.2, 2.4.3.\n- **Shift+Tab:** Closes the menu and allows focus to move to the previous tabbable element in page order. WCAG 2.1.2, 2.4.3.\n\n### Typeahead\n\nRecommended for menus with 5-8 items:\n\n- Printable character keys move focus to the next item whose label starts with the typed character.\n- Repeated characters cycle through matching items.\n- Disabled items may be included in typeahead focus but must not activate.\n\nThis supports efficient keyboard navigation and aligns with APG menu expectations. WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard.\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n### Focus On Open\n\nWhen the button opens the menu, focus should move into the menu, not remain on the button.\n\nDefault behavior:\n\n- Enter, Space, or Arrow Down opens the menu and focuses the first enabled menu item.\n- Arrow Up opens the menu and focuses the last enabled menu item.\n\nThis follows the APG Menu Button pattern and prevents screen reader users from having to discover that a menu opened somewhere below while focus stayed on the trigger.\n\n### Focus Within Menu\n\nUse roving tabindex or `aria-activedescendant`.\n\nRecommended approach for this React component: **roving tabindex**.\n\n- Only the currently focused menu item has `tabindex=\"0\"`.\n- Other menu items have `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n- Arrow keys update the active item and move DOM focus.\n- The menu container itself is not part of the normal tab order.\n\nRoving tabindex is straightforward to test and works well with native button or link menu items. WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order, WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\n### Focus On Close\n\nFocus restoration rules:\n\n- **Escape:** Close menu and restore focus to the trigger button.\n- **Click outside:** Close menu and leave focus where the user clicked if the click target is focusable; otherwise restore focus to the trigger button.\n- **Selecting an item:** Close menu. If the action keeps the user on the same page, return focus to the trigger button unless the action opens a dialog, navigates, deletes the trigger, or intentionally moves focus to a result/status.\n- **Tab out:** Close menu and allow browser focus to move naturally to the next tabbable element.\n\nIf the menu trigger is removed after an action, focus must move to a logical fallback: the next related action button, the parent row/card heading, or a status message with `tabindex=\"-1\"`. WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n\n### Focus Trap Decision\n\nDo not implement a modal-style focus trap.\n\nA dropdown menu is a transient popup, not a modal dialog. Focus is managed inside the menu while it is open, but users must be able to leave with Escape, Tab, Shift+Tab, or pointer interaction. A trap would risk violating WCAG 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap.\n\n### Visual Focus Indicator\n\nThe trigger and each menu item must have a visible focus indicator.\n\nRequirements:\n\n- Minimum 3:1 contrast between focused and unfocused states. WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible, WCAG 2.4.13 Focus Appearance.\n- Use `:focus-visible` for keyboard focus indication.\n- Prefer a two-color focus indicator, such as outline plus box-shadow, so focus remains visible against varied backgrounds.\n- Menu item focus must not rely on background color alone; include either an outline, border, icon, or clear visual shape change. WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual Indicator | Programmatic Indicator | ARIA Attribute | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Menu closed | Dropdown not visible; optional chevron points down | Trigger exposes collapsed state | `aria-expanded=\"false\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Menu open | Dropdown visible; optional chevron points up | Trigger exposes expanded state; menu exists in accessibility tree | `aria-expanded=\"true\"`, `role=\"menu\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Menu item focused | Outline/background/shape change | DOM focus on item | `tabindex=\"0\"` on active item | 2.4.7, 2.4.13, 4.1.2 |\n| Menu item unfocused | Normal item styling | Not in tab sequence | `tabindex=\"-1\"` | 2.4.3 |\n| Menu item disabled | Dimmed plus disabled text/icon treatment | Disabled state announced | `aria-disabled=\"true\"` | 1.4.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Item selected/activated | Action runs; menu closes | Activation through native click/key event | Native button/link behavior with `role=\"menuitem\"` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Loading action, if async | Spinner plus \u201cLoading\u201d or \u201cSaving\u201d text | Status announcement | `aria-busy`, `role=\"status\"` if needed | 4.1.3 |\n| Error after action, if async | Error text plus icon/color | Error announced and associated with affected control/region | `role=\"alert\"` or `aria-live=\"assertive\"` | 3.3.1, 4.1.3 |\n\n### ARIA Attribute Requirements\n\n**Trigger button:**\n\n- `aria-haspopup=\"menu\"`: required to identify popup type. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-expanded`: required and synchronized with actual open state. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-controls`: recommended to associate trigger and menu. WCAG 1.3.1, 4.1.2.\n\n**Menu:**\n\n- `role=\"menu\"`: required for APG menu pattern. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-labelledby`: recommended to name the menu from the trigger button. WCAG 1.3.1, 4.1.2.\n\n**Menu items:**\n\n- `role=\"menuitem\"` for command items. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-disabled=\"true\"` for disabled items. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `tabindex=\"0\"` on active item and `tabindex=\"-1\"` on inactive items for roving tabindex. WCAG 2.4.3, 4.1.2.\n\n**Optional submenu trigger:**\n\nNested submenus are out of the initial scope unless explicitly required. If included:\n\n- Parent item uses `aria-haspopup=\"menu\"`.\n- Parent item uses `aria-expanded`.\n- Right Arrow opens submenu.\n- Left Arrow closes submenu and returns focus to parent item.\n- Escape closes all open menus and restores focus to original trigger.\n\nNested submenus increase risk and should receive a separate a11y-critic review before implementation.\n\n---\n\n## Screen Reader Experience\n\nExpected screen reader behavior with NVDA and JAWS:\n\n1. User tabs to the trigger.\n   - Announcement: \u201cActions, menu button, collapsed.\u201d\n2. User presses Enter, Space, or Arrow Down.\n   - Menu opens.\n   - Focus moves to the first enabled menu item.\n   - Announcement: first item name and role, for example \u201cEdit, menu item.\u201d\n3. User presses Arrow Down.\n   - Focus moves to the next item.\n   - Announcement: next item name and role.\n4. User lands on a disabled item.\n   - Announcement should include disabled/unavailable state.\n   - Item must not activate.\n5. User presses Escape.\n   - Menu closes.\n   - Focus returns to trigger button.\n   - Announcement returns to button context, ideally \u201cActions, menu button, collapsed.\u201d\n6. User activates an item with Enter or Space.\n   - Item action occurs.\n   - Menu closes.\n   - Focus goes to the trigger or to the next logical destination for that action.\n\nDo not use `title` as the accessible name for the button or menu items. Use visible text or `aria-label` only when visible text cannot provide sufficient context. WCAG 2.4.6, 4.1.2.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\n- Text and menu item labels must meet 4.5:1 contrast against the background. WCAG 1.4.3.\n- Focus indicators must meet at least 3:1 contrast and satisfy WCAG 2.4.7 and 2.4.13.\n- Menu item hover/focus/disabled states must not rely on color alone. Pair color with outline, icon, opacity plus text, or shape. WCAG 1.4.1.\n- Trigger and menu items should have minimum 24x24 CSS pixel targets, with 44x44 recommended for touch-friendly layouts. WCAG 2.5.8.\n- Text should use relative units and remain usable at 200% zoom. WCAG 1.4.4.\n- At 400% zoom / 320px equivalent width, the menu must fit within the viewport or reposition without horizontal scrolling. WCAG 1.4.10.\n- Any chevron or decorative icon should be `aria-hidden=\"true\"` because expanded/collapsed state is already communicated through `aria-expanded`. WCAG 1.1.1, 4.1.2.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n- Button label should be descriptive: \u201cActions\u201d is acceptable if context is clear; otherwise use \u201cActions for [item name].\u201d WCAG 2.4.6.\n- Menu item labels must describe the action directly: \u201cEdit,\u201d \u201cDuplicate,\u201d \u201cArchive,\u201d \u201cDelete.\u201d Avoid vague labels like \u201cOption 1.\u201d WCAG 2.4.6.\n- Destructive actions should be clearly named, not represented by icon alone. WCAG 2.4.6.\n- If an item opens a new window or external destination, include that in the accessible name or visible text. WCAG 2.4.4, 3.2.2.\n- Icons inside menu items should be decorative unless they add meaning not present in text. Decorative icons use `aria-hidden=\"true\"`. WCAG 1.1.1.\n- DOM order must match visual order of items. WCAG 1.3.2.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Automated Testing\n\nRun axe-core against the closed and open states.\n\nCheck:\n\n- Button has accessible name.\n- ARIA attributes are valid.\n- `aria-controls` references an existing menu ID when rendered.\n- `role=\"menu\"` contains valid `menuitem` children.\n- Disabled items expose `aria-disabled`.\n- Color contrast passes.\n- No hidden menu items remain focusable when the menu is closed.\n\nAutomated tools will not fully verify keyboard behavior, focus restoration, or screen reader announcement quality.\n\n### DOM Verification\n\nRequired DOM checks:\n\n- Trigger has `aria-haspopup=\"menu\"`.\n- Trigger `aria-expanded` changes from `\"false\"` to `\"true\"` on open and back to `\"false\"` on close.\n- Menu has `role=\"menu\"`.\n- Items have `role=\"menuitem\"`.\n- Disabled items have `aria-disabled=\"true\"`.\n- Only one menu item has `tabindex=\"0\"` while menu is open.\n- Closed menu is removed from DOM or hidden from both visual and accessibility access.\n\n### Keyboard Test Cases\n\n- Tab reaches trigger button in logical page order.\n- Enter opens menu and focuses first enabled item.\n- Space opens menu and focuses first enabled item.\n- Arrow Down from trigger opens menu and focuses first enabled item.\n- Arrow Up from trigger opens menu and focuses last enabled item.\n- Arrow Down inside menu moves focus to next item.\n- Arrow Up inside menu moves focus to previous item.\n- Home moves focus to first item.\n- End moves focus to last item.\n- Enter activates enabled focused item and closes menu.\n- Space activates enabled focused item and closes menu.\n- Disabled item receives focus if included in arrow order but does not activate.\n- Escape closes menu and restores focus to trigger.\n- Tab closes menu and moves focus to next tabbable page element.\n- Shift+Tab closes menu and moves focus to previous tabbable page element.\n- Click outside closes menu without leaving hidden focusable content behind.\n\n### Screen Reader Test Cases\n\nTest with NVDA and JAWS:\n\n- Trigger announces as menu button with collapsed state.\n- Opening announces first focused menu item.\n- Arrow navigation announces each item name and role.\n- Disabled item announces unavailable/disabled.\n- Escape returns focus to trigger and collapsed state is exposed.\n- Selecting an item does not leave screen reader focus in removed menu content.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe component is accessible when:\n\n- It follows the APG Menu Button pattern.\n- The trigger exposes name, role, popup type, and expanded state.\n- Focus moves into the menu on open.\n- Arrow keys navigate the menu items.\n- Escape closes and restores focus.\n- Disabled items are programmatically disabled and cannot activate.\n- Visual focus is clearly visible on trigger and menu items.\n- Closed menu content is not keyboard-focusable or exposed as active content.\n- Keyboard-only and screen reader users can complete the same actions as pointer users.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Menu Button Trigger\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Reusable React menu button component\n- Component tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<button\n  type=\"button\"\n  aria-haspopup=\"menu\"\n  aria-expanded=\"[true|false]\"\n  aria-controls=\"[menu-id]\"\n>\n  Actions\n</button>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-haspopup=\"menu\"`: identifies popup menu. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-expanded`: communicates open/closed state. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-controls`: associates trigger with menu. WCAG 1.3.1, 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Enter/Space opens menu and focuses first enabled item.\n- Arrow Down opens menu and focuses first enabled item.\n- Arrow Up opens menu and focuses last enabled item.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Trigger is tabbable.\n- Trigger has accessible name.\n- `aria-expanded` toggles correctly.\n- Opening moves focus to menu item.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** Verify APG Menu Button mapping and trigger ARIA correctness.\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Menu and Menu Items\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<div role=\"menu\" aria-labelledby=\"[button-id]\">\n  <button role=\"menuitem\" tabindex=\"0\">Edit</button>\n  <button role=\"menuitem\" tabindex=\"-1\">Duplicate</button>\n  <button role=\"menuitem\" aria-disabled=\"true\" tabindex=\"-1\">Archive</button>\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `role=\"menu\"`: identifies popup as menu. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-labelledby`: names menu from trigger. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- `role=\"menuitem\"`: identifies command items. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-disabled=\"true\"`: exposes disabled state. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `tabindex`: implements roving focus. WCAG 2.4.3.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Arrow Up/Down move focus.\n- Home/End jump to first/last item.\n- Enter/Space activate enabled items.\n- Disabled items do not activate.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Arrow navigation works.\n- Roving tabindex updates.\n- Disabled item is announced and blocked from activation.\n- DOM roles are present on correct elements.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** Verify menu role structure and roving tabindex behavior.\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: Close Behavior and Focus Restoration\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Escape closes menu and restores focus to trigger.\n- Tab and Shift+Tab close menu and move naturally through page focus order.\n- Outside click closes menu.\n- Selection closes menu and moves focus according to action result.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Escape restores focus to trigger.\n- Tab does not create a keyboard trap.\n- Closed menu has no focusable hidden items.\n- Focus is not lost after item activation.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard.\n- WCAG 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap.\n- WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n- WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** Verify focus restoration and no keyboard trap.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus Areas |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Trigger implementation | APG Menu Button mapping, accessible name, `aria-haspopup`, `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls` |\n| 2 | Menu item implementation | `role=\"menu\"`, `role=\"menuitem\"`, disabled item behavior, roving tabindex |\n| 3 | Focus and keyboard behavior | Open focus movement, arrow navigation, Escape close, Tab behavior, focus restoration |\n| 4 | Visual and screen reader validation | Focus indicator contrast, announcements in NVDA/JAWS, disabled state announcement |\n\n---\n\n## Failure Modes This Plan Prevents\n\n- Treating the menu as a disclosure and leaving focus on the trigger after open.\n- Opening the menu visually while `aria-expanded` remains stale.\n- Rendering hidden menu items that remain tabbable.\n- Using clickable `<div>` elements instead of native buttons or links.\n- Making disabled items visually dimmed but still activatable.\n- Adding a modal focus trap to a non-modal dropdown.\n- Relying on color alone for focus or disabled state.\n- Using `title` instead of a real accessible name.\n- Forgetting Escape close and focus restoration.\n\n## References\n\n- WAI-ARIA APG Menu Button Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/menu-button/\n- WAI-ARIA APG Menu and Menubar Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/menubar/\n- WCAG 2.2 Quick Reference: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/quickref/\n- ARIA Authoring Practices Guide: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/",
